return page.evaluate(() => {
  // Find all elements inside the grid area that have a non-transparent background
  const gridRoot = document.querySelector('.sv-grid-root');
  if (!gridRoot) return 'no sv-grid-root';

  const results = [];
  const walker = document.createTreeWalker(gridRoot.parentElement, NodeFilter.SHOW_ELEMENT);
  let node;
  while ((node = walker.nextNode())) {
    const cs = getComputedStyle(node);
    const bg = cs.backgroundColor;
    if (bg !== 'rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)' && bg !== 'transparent') {
      results.push({
        tag: node.tagName,
        class: node.className.toString().slice(0, 80),
        bg,
        sgBg: cs.getPropertyValue('--sg-bg').trim().slice(0, 40),
      });
      if (results.length >= 10) break;
    }
  }
  return results;
});

data.reasoningText:
Found it! The CSS in SvGrid.svelte has:

```css
.sv-grid-column,
.sv-grid-cell {
  box-sizing: border-box;
  overflow: hidden;
  text-overflow: ellipsis;
  white-space: nowrap;
  background: #fff;  /* ← HARDCODED WHITE! */
  user-select: none;
}
```

This is `background: #fff` - a hardcoded white background. And then separate rules like `background: var(--sg-bg, #fff)` are elsewhere in the file for different elements.


The scoped CSS in the Svelte component gets compiled with a hash suffix, so the actual rule becomes something like `.sv-grid-column.svelte-17xre14` with specificity `0-2-0`. That means any global CSS trying to override it would need higher specificity to win out, but since this is baked into the compiled component, it's hard to override from outside.

I'm noticing there are actually two different patterns here—some places use hardcoded `#fff` directly on cells and columns, while other elements like the root or pinned rows use `var(--sg-bg, #fff)` with a CSS variable fallback. So the component isn't consistently using the variable approach everywhere.

To override the hardcoded values, I'd need to use a selector with higher specificity than Svelte's scoped rules. I could either apply `!important` with a dark mode class selector, or use a more specific selector like `html.dark` to bump up the specificity above what Svelte's class hash provides. So `(0,2,1)` beats `(0,2,0)`, meaning the dark mode selector would override the component's default styling. The docs actually confirm this is the intended approach—they mention the app stylesheet can override `.sv-grid-cell`. I'll add CSS rules targeting `html.dark .sv-grid-column`, `html.dark .sv-grid-cell`, and `html.dark .sv-grid-head` to apply the dark mode colors, but I should verify there aren't other elements I'm missing.

